[3] Colombia (Barranquilla)
Date: Thu 8 Sep 2011
Source: El Heraldo, Local [in Spanish, trans. Mod. JT, abbreviated,
edited]
http://www.elheraldo.co/local/decretan-alerta-roja-por-casos-de-sarampi-n-en-barranquilla-36923


Health authorities in Barranquilla decreed this afternoon [8 Sep 2011]
a red alert for measles cases in the city, which has already affected
4 people with another as yet unconfirmed case. The news was announced
by the District Health Secretary, Martha Rodriguez. By declaring a red
alert on the basis of 4 confirmed cases and one unconfirmed case, the
health authorities are hoping to prevent further circulation of the
infection. "The EPS, private practitioners and everyone must work
towards cooperation in this effort," she said.

Regarding these new cases, the Secretary of Health said that the only
link is a girl who came from Brazil and who is attending the same
religious school. The 1st case was the child who came from Brazil,
followed subsequently by her mother and brother. The 4th case is not a
relative but a child who regularly attends the same religious school
as the others. The official reported that a 5th case is suspected.

The District Health Secretariat has called for parents to bring their
children to be vaccinated at places arranged by health officials on
Saturday and Sunday [10-11 Sep 2011].

To prevent further transmission of the disease, free vaccination will
be provided for 209 000 children [291 000 in the following report]
aged between 11 and 19 who have not already received 2 immunisations.
The Ministry of Health stated that most of this population has been
identified so far through the school system. However, parents with
children at private schools have not given permission for vaccination
of their children.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-ESP <promed@promedmail.org>

[Barranquilla is a coastal city and municipality located in northern
Colombia, near the Caribbean Sea. It is the capital of the Atlantico
department and is the largest industrial city and port in the
Colombian Caribbean region, with a population of over one million,
making it Colombia's 4th most populous city after Bogota, Medellin and
Cali.

The city is the core of the Metropolitan Area of Barranquilla, which
is constituted by the municipalities of Soledad, Galapa, Malambo, and
Puerto Colombia. - Mod.CP]

******
[4] Colombia (Atlantico & Bolivar)
Date: Fri 9 Sep 2011
Source: Caracol Radio [in Spanish, machine trans. abbreviated &
edited]
http://www.caracol.com.co/nota.aspx?id=1544634


A Ministry of Health official, Martha Rodriguez, said that a red alert
has been declared following confirmation of a 4th cases of measles.
This official expressed concern that some private schools [in the
department of Atlantico] had been reported to have denied access to
vaccination staff. The official added that educational institutions
cannot be allowed to adopt policies contrary to the benefit of the
wider community. Parents should bring their children to be vaccinated
at places designated by health authorities this Saturday and Sunday
[11-12 Sep 2011].

Similarly, the Departmental Secretariat of Health announced an amber
health alert throughout the Department of Bolivar and asked employers
in this region of the country to be vigilant for symptoms of rubella
and measles, which might be displayed by patients admitted to
hospitals in the department of Bolivar, as a consequence of the
confirmation of the 4 cases of measles in the city of Barranquilla
[Atlantico department].

The Ministry of Social Protection has distributed 931 000 doses of
vaccines against measles and rubella in the Atlantic coast region as a
preventive measure as follows: in the Atlantico department 164 000
doses, 291 000 doses in Barranquilla, 108 000 doses in Bolivar, 128
000 doses in Cartagena, 108 000 doses in Magdalena, and 132 000 doses
in Santa Marta.

--
