[5] USA (Wisconsin)
Date: Thu 8 Sep 2011
Source: Witi-TV, Milwaukee [edited]
http://www.fox6now.com/news/witi-20110907-measles-case-in-milwaukee,0,3205781.story


The Milwaukee Health Department identified a confirmed case of measles
in a Milwaukee child Wednesday afternoon [7 Sep 2011]. Officials only
say the victim is a refugee child who came to Milwaukee with his
family in late August 2011. He/she may have carried the disease from
abroad but was not contagious while on the plane. The patient is
currently being hospitalized.

Measles is a very contagious and easily-spread illness caused by a
virus. According to the U.S. National Library of Medicine: "The
infection is spread by contact with droplets from the nose, mouth or
throat of an infected person. Sneezing and coughing can put
contaminated droplets into the air."

Symptoms usually begin 8-12 days after you are exposed to the virus.
Symptoms may include bloodshot eyes, cough, fever, sensitivity to
light, muscle pain, rash, redness of the eyes, sore throat and tiny
white spots inside the mouth. There is no specific treatment for
measles. However, bed rest, humidified air and acetaminophen products
like Tylenol may relieve some of the symptoms.

Paul Biedrzychki of the Milwaukee Health Department says the disease
is especially dangerous to young children, people with compromised
immune systems, and pregnant women. The last time Milwaukee dealt with
a case of measles was 2008.

If you have questions or concerns about symptoms you're seeing, call
the Milwaukee Health Department at 414-286-3521 between the hours of 8
a.m. and 4:30 p.m. Monday through Friday.

