******
Australia
[6] New Zealand
Date: Tue 6 Sep 2010
Source: Voxy.co.nz [abbreviated and edited]
http://www.voxy.co.nz/health/auckland-measles-outbreak-now-fourth-month/5/100571


The Auckland Regional Public Health Service can confirm 119 cases of
measles in the Auckland region as of this morning [6 Sep 2011, an
increase of 2 confirmed cases since 30 Aug 2011. - Mod.CP]. Ten
contacts are in quarantine. Nine cases have required hospitalisation
during this outbreak. Most cases have occurred in West Auckland with
some spread to Central Auckland, North Shore, and Manukau.

The measles outbreak is now into its 4th month. Medical Officer of
Health Dr Richard Hoskins says: "Currently, 5 schools and pre-schools
have been asked to advise parents to exclude their child if their
child has not been fully immunised (2 measles vaccines).

"To check if your child is up-to-date with their immunisations,
contact your GP. This information can also be found in your Well Child
Health Book or, if your child is under 7 years old, you can check the
National Immunisation Register by calling:

- Waitemata DHB NIR (09) 838 1852
- Auckland DHB NIR (09) 638 0393 or (09) 638 0394
- Counties Manukau DHB NIR 0800 454 375

Measles is highly infectious, so please phone your doctor or GP 1st
before going to the surgery; symptoms include fever, cough, blocked
nose, sore red eyes. If you think you or anyone in your family might
have measles, contact your doctor or Healthline on 0800 611 116 for
advice." says Dr Hoskins.

Seven confirmed cases of rubella have been notified in the region
[unchanged since 22 Aug 2011. - Mod.CP]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Reports of measles cases and outbreaks are beginning decline,
suggesting either reporting fatigue or that enhanced measles
vaccination coverage may be beginning to take effect.

Commencing in September 2010, nearly 100 million children across China
were targeted for measles vaccination, in one of the largest public
health exercises attempted, in an effort to eliminate measles in China
by 2012 (UN News Centre:
http://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=35799&Cr=measles&Cr1).
The steady stream of reports reaching HealthMap from different
provinces of China (but not relayed by ProMED-mail because of our
translation limitations) indicate that this aim has not yet been
achieved, although the case numbers are not excessively high in
relation to population size. - Mod.CP]
